I get a lot of DMs asking for product reccos and suggestions, but so it happens that I’m unable to reply to all how much ever I try! So I feel this new series would help you guys in picking products you need and answer a few of your queries for sure. 
So let me start with this @thetribeconcepts collagen boosting shilajitadi thailam. I’ve mentioned this one in my stories too but here’s a quick review for you all. 
I’ve been using this for over 3 months now and let me tell you it’s one product I literally cannot do without! I use it both in my AM-PM routine. It’s a lightweight face oil and is suitable for all skin types. An incredible product for those looking to improve the skin elasticity, firmness. prevent early ageing signs and boost radiance. Made with potent ingredients, this power packed product is highly beneficial to vitalize your skin. I feel it is quite effective as I have noticed a visible change in my skin since the time I’ve started using it. ❤️
How to use: Take a few drops and Massage on your face and neck. Leave for 30 minutes and then wash off with a mild cleanser. 
You need not rinse if you’re a dry skin type. 
I often use this oil with my gua sha too to induce good blood flow and bring out the glow❤️
Whether I’ll purchase it again, definitely a YES! 

It’s priced at ₹1499 but you can get it at 15% off right now on www.vanitywagon.in 🌿 ❤️
.
Hope you enjoyed reading this review! If there’s any specific product you want me to talk about, let me know in the comments and I’ll take it up next time!

latestIgtvVideos.title: Facial massage using Kansa wand
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Showing how to massage your face using a Kansa Wand! This one by @shankaranaturalsindia 
Kansa wand is a traditional Indian face massage tool. 
It’s made of Copper- which helps reduce inflammation and maintain the strength of the skin;  Tin that helps maintain the skin collagen.; And zinc- that helps rejuvenate the skin.

Kansa wand massage has numerous benefits:
It Revitalizes and nourishes the skin. 
It helps improve circulation and free movement of nutrients into cells and ensures the skin is healthy and aglow. It Supports the release of excess heat and acidity. 
It Tones facial muscles.
Balances pH of the skin.
It Removes stress from the body and mind.
Calms down inflammations, caused by dryness and dosha imbalance.

It’s super easy to use and you can do it any time of the day. 
This is available on www.vanitywagon.in @vanitywagon

latestPosts.caption:
Can’t be thankful enough to @businessworldbw for this incredible recognition! It feels surreal to have won the #bwwellbeing40under40 award. 🤍💫

When me and Prateek started out on a journey to introduce India to “Clean Beauty”, little did we know how it was going to impact us, not just professionally, but also personally. It made us more aware of our decisions and more conscious of our actions. It transformed our lifestyles and defined how we were going to leave our footprint on this planet.

@vanitywagon will turn five in a few months and I am only grateful for all that we have achieved so far and where we have arrived. But this is just the beginning and we still have a long way to go! 

I’m extremely grateful to the entire jury at @businessworldbw for this honour. It only motivates me to work harder and continue doing my best in the future. 💪🏻

#reels#bwwellbeing #businessworld#award#entrepreneur #womeninbusiness #reelsinstagram #gratitude #recognition #startup #vanitywagon #cleanbeauty #bw40under40 #womenentrepreneurs #womeninwellness

Gratitude 🙏🏻 

#repost • @hercircleofficial The meaning of the term ‘clean beauty’ is somewhat confusing to many thanks to the fact that we don’t have a fixed definition set for it. Along with other buzzwords like ‘organic’ and ‘green,’ brands market their products as clean but what does it actually mean? As we interviewed Naina Ruhail, co-founder of India’s first clean beauty marketplace Vanity Wagon, we asked her to decipher it for us. “Clean for me, would be products that are mindfully created and ethically sourced without any proven or suspected toxic ingredients,” she explains. “It basically means that these are safe to use on your body and have transparent labelling of ingredients. ‘Clean beauty’ is a whole another spectrum; an umbrella which houses all the buzzwords–including vegan, plant-based, cruelty-free, natural, and silicone, sulphate and paraben-free–under it,” she adds. To know more about how she went about her journey in the beauty space, head to the link in bio.

@nainaruhail @vanitywagon
